		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I really like that jello! Both actually <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /> The aiming is a great addition. Things being at different angles feels commonly accepted for this sort of style. It might even actually add something to the soup, now when i think about it. A little whacky perspectives can go a long way to catch interest. European medieval, baroque and traditional japanese art styles (which i know terribly little about) does this in varying forms all the time, not to mention cubism. I wouldn't worry about it too much.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I thought that the &quot;damaged/crushed&quot; tiles were ok and not in a different style.</div><br />I'm sorry, i could have been a lot more specific. I think most of them are! The one that stands out to me is the one for the bricks, which feels like a representation of crushed brick, but perhaps not a direct derivate of the bricks that were there in prior to crushing. <br /><br />Here's a quick mockup (though in a somewhat different style)<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
